1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:01,040
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:04,560
Mr Lockwood visits Wuthering Heights

3
00:00:09,440 --> 00:00:15,200
I have just returned from a visit to my 
landlord, Mr Heathcliff. I am delighted  

4
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:21,840
with the house I am renting from him. Thrushcross 
Grange is miles away from any town or village.  

5
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:29,840
That suits me perfectly. And the scenery 
here in Yorkshire is so beautiful!

6
00:00:30,560 --> 00:00:33,520
Mr Heathcliff, in fact, is my only neighbour,  

7
00:00:34,160 --> 00:00:39,680
and I think his character is similar to 
mine. He does not like people either.

8
00:00:41,760 --> 00:00:46,080
'My name is Lockwood,' I said, when 
I met him at the gate to his house.  

9
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:52,720
'I'm renting Thrushcross Grange from you. I 
just wanted to come and introduce myself.'

10
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:59,120
He said nothing, but frowned, and 
did not encourage me to enter.  

11
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:03,760
After a while, however, he 
decided to invite me in.

12
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:13,600
'Joseph, take Mr Lockwood's horse!' he called. 
'And bring up some wine from the cellar!'  

13
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:20,080
Joseph was a very old servant, 
with a sour expression on his face.  

14
00:01:21,040 --> 00:01:26,160
He looked crossly up at me as he took my horse.

15
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:34,880
'God help us! A visitor!' he muttered to himself. 
Perhaps there were no other servants, I thought.  

16
00:01:35,680 --> 00:01:39,840
And it seemed that Mr Heathcliff 
hardly ever received guests.

17
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:48,640
His house is called Wuthering Heights. The 
name means 'a windswept house on a hill',  

18
00:01:49,440 --> 00:01:55,360
and it is a very good description. The 
trees around the house do not grow straight,  

19
00:01:55,920 --> 00:02:01,200
but are bent by the north wind, which 
blows over the moors every day of the year.  

20
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:09,200
Fortunately, the house is strongly built, and 
is not damaged even by the worst winter storms.  

21
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:15,520
The name 'Earnshaw' is cut into 
a stone over the front door.

22
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:25,280
Mr Heathcliff and I entered the huge main room. It 
could have been any Yorkshire farmhouse kitchen,  

23
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:30,880
except that there was no sign of cooking, 
and no farmer sitting at the table.  

24
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:39,760
Mr Heathcliff certainly does not look like 
a farmer. His hair and skin are dark, like a  

25
00:02:39,760 --> 00:02:47,200
gipsy's, but he has the manners of a gentleman. He 
could perhaps take more care with his appearance,  

26
00:02:47,920 --> 00:02:54,080
but he is handsome. I think 
he is proud, and also unhappy.

27
00:02:56,320 --> 00:02:58,880
We sat down by the fire, in silence.

28
00:03:01,040 --> 00:03:09,200
'Joseph!' shouted Mr Heathcliff. No answer 
came from the cellar, so he dived down there,  

29
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:13,200
leaving me alone with several 
rather fierce-looking dogs.  

30
00:03:14,560 --> 00:03:22,800
Suddenly one of them jumped angrily up at me, and 
in a moment all the others were attacking me. From  

31
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:31,880
every shadowy corner in the great room appeared 
a growling animal, ready to kill me, it seemed.

32
00:03:31,880 --> 00:03:42,000
'Help! Mr Heathcliff! Help!' I shouted, trying to 
keep the dogs back. My landlord and his servant  

33
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:49,040
were in no hurry to help, and could not have 
climbed the cellar steps more slowly, but luckily  

34
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:55,200
a woman, who I supposed was the housekeeper, 
rushed into the room to calm the dogs.

35
00:03:57,280 --> 00:04:03,760
'What the devil is the matter?' Mr Heathcliff 
asked me rudely, when he finally entered the room.

36
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:14,320
'Your dogs, sir!' I replied. 'You shouldn't 
leave a stranger with them. They're dangerous.'

37
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:18,240
'Come, come, Mr Lockwood. Have some wine.  

38
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:27,840
We don't often have strangers here, and I'm afraid 
neither I nor my dogs are used to receiving them.'

39
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:37,040
I could not feel offended after this, and 
accepted the wine. We sat drinking and talking  

40
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:45,840
together for a while. I suggested visiting him 
tomorrow. He did not seem eager to see me again,  

41
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:55,840
but I shall go anyway. I am interested in 
him, even if he isn't interested in me.

42
00:04:56,560 --> 00:05:03,200
Two days later Yesterday afternoon 
was misty and bitterly cold,  

43
00:05:03,920 --> 00:05:09,840
but I walked the four miles to Wuthering Heights 
and arrived just as it was beginning to snow.  

44
00:05:10,640 --> 00:05:15,360
I banged on the front door for ten 
minutes, getting colder and colder.  

45
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:21,360
Finally Joseph's head appeared at a 
window of one of the farm buildings.

46
00:05:23,280 --> 00:05:26,160
'What do you want?' he growled.

47
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:31,360
'Could you let me in?' I asked desperately.

48
00:05:32,720 --> 00:05:40,640
He shook his head. 'There's only Mrs Heathcliff 
indoors, and she won't open the door to you.'

49
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:49,680
Just then a young man appeared and called me to 
follow him. We went through the back door and  

50
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:57,280
into the big room where I had been before. I was 
delighted to see a warm fire and a table full of  

51
00:05:57,280 --> 00:06:05,840
food. And this time there was a woman sitting by 
the fire. She must be Mrs Heathcliff, I thought.  

52
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:12,960
I had not imagined my landlord was married. She 
looked at me coldly without saying anything.

53
00:06:15,200 --> 00:06:19,840
'Terrible weather!' I remarked. There was silence.

54
00:06:22,560 --> 00:06:28,640
'What a beautiful animal!' I tried again, 
pointing to one of the dogs that had attacked me.  

55
00:06:30,320 --> 00:06:37,520
She still said nothing, but got up to make 
the tea. She was only about seventeen, with  

56
00:06:37,520 --> 00:06:44,720
the most beautiful little face I had ever seen. 
Her golden wavy hair fell around her shoulders.

57
00:06:47,120 --> 00:06:51,440
'Have you been invited to 
tea?' she asked me crossly.

58
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:57,760
'No, but you are the proper 
person to invite me,' I smiled.

59
00:06:59,760 --> 00:07:05,280
For some reason this really annoyed her. She 
stopped making the tea, and threw herself  

60
00:07:05,280 --> 00:07:11,200
angrily back in her chair. Meanwhile the 
young man was staring aggressively at me.  

61
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:16,320
He looked like a farm worker, but 
seemed to be part of the family.  

62
00:07:17,680 --> 00:07:23,120
I did not feel at all comfortable. 
At last Heathcliff came in.

63
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:29,840
'Here I am, sir, as I 
promised!' I said cheerfully.

64
00:07:30,640 --> 00:07:36,080
'You shouldn't have come,' he answered, 
shaking the snow off his clothes.  

65
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:39,760
'You'll never find your way back in the dark.'

66
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:46,720
'Perhaps you could lend me a servant to 
guide me back to the Grange?' I asked.

67
00:07:47,920 --> 00:07:56,080
'No, I couldn't. There aren't any servants 
here except Joseph and the housekeeper. Get  

68
00:07:56,080 --> 00:08:02,640
the tea ready, will you?' he added fiercely to the 
young woman. I was shocked by his unpleasantness.

69
00:08:04,960 --> 00:08:11,840
We sat down to eat. I tried to make conversation 
with the three silent people round the table.

70
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:19,440
'How happy you must be, Mr Heathcliff,' I began, 
'in this quiet place, with your wife and-'

71
00:08:20,560 --> 00:08:25,840
'My wife! My wife's ghost, you mean?'

72
00:08:27,360 --> 00:08:33,120
I suddenly realized I had made a 
serious mistake. So his wife was dead!  

73
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:40,560
Of course he was too old to be married to that 
young girl. She must be married to the young  

74
00:08:40,560 --> 00:08:46,640
man next to me, who was drinking his tea out of 
a bowl and eating his bread with unwashed hands.  

75
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:51,040
Perhaps the poor girl had found no one better to  

76
00:08:51,040 --> 00:08:56,160
marry in this uninhabited area. I 
turned politely to the young man.

77
00:08:58,080 --> 00:09:07,840
'Ah, so you are this lady's husband!' This was 
worse than before. His face went red, and he  

78
00:09:07,840 --> 00:09:14,480
seemed only just able to stop himself hitting 
me. He muttered something I could not hear.

79
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:24,640
'Wrong again, Mr Lockwood,' said Mr 
Heathcliff. 'No, her husband, my son,  

80
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:35,840
is dead. This, 'he added', looking scornfully 
at the young man, 'is certainly not my son.'

81
00:09:37,440 --> 00:09:42,000
'My name is Hareton Earnshaw,' 
growled the young man.

82
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:48,560
We finished our meal in silence, 
and when I looked out of the window,  

83
00:09:48,560 --> 00:09:50,720
all I could see was darkness and snow.

84
00:09:53,040 --> 00:09:59,520
'I don't think I can get home without a 
guide,' I said politely. No one answered me.  

85
00:10:00,640 --> 00:10:01,680
I turned to the woman.

86
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:10,000
'Mrs Heathcliff,' I begged, 
'What can I do? Please help me!'

87
00:10:11,040 --> 00:10:15,200
'Take the road you came on,' 
she replied without interest,  

88
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:18,880
opening a book. 'That's the 
best advice I can give.'

89
00:10:20,960 --> 00:10:25,440
'Mr Heathcliff, I'll have to stay 
here for the night!' I told him.

90
00:10:27,040 --> 00:10:31,120
'I hope that will teach you not to 
walk over the moors in bad weather,'  

91
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:40,800
he answered. 'I don't keep guest bedrooms. 
You can share a bed with Hareton or Joseph.'

92
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:48,960
I was so angry with them all that I could not stay 
there a moment longer, and rushed out into the  

93
00:10:48,960 --> 00:10:56,400
darkness. I saw Joseph by the back door, caught 
hold of the lamp he was carrying, and ran with  

94
00:10:56,400 --> 00:11:03,280
it to the gate. But the dogs chased after me and 
attacked me, and I was soon knocked to the ground.  

95
00:11:04,720 --> 00:11:07,600
Heathcliff and Hareton 
stood at the door, laughing,  

96
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:15,360
as I shouted at the dogs and tried to get up. In 
the end I was again rescued by the housekeeper,  

97
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:19,360
Zillah, who ordered away the 
dogs and helped me to my feet.

98
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:26,160
I was so bruised and exhausted that I 
did not feel strong enough to walk home,  

99
00:11:27,440 --> 00:11:32,080
and although I did not want to, I had 
to spend the night at Wuthering Heights.  

100
00:11:33,520 --> 00:11:41,840
Nobody wished me goodnight, as Zillah 
took me upstairs to find a bed for me.
 
 

101
00:11:43,360 --> 00:11:44,160
CHAPTER TWO

102
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:47,040
Catherine Earnshaw's room

103
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:57,120
'Quietly, sir!' whispered the housekeeper, 
as we climbed up the dark stairs.  

104
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:03,120
'My master will be angry if he discovers 
which bedroom you're sleeping in.  

105
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:07,840
For some reason he doesn't 
want anyone to sleep there,  

106
00:12:08,720 --> 00:12:16,160
I don't know why. They're strange people in 
this house, you know. Here's the room, sir.'

107
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:19,840
But I was too tired to listen.

108
00:12:21,520 --> 00:12:27,520
'Thank you, Zillah,' I said, and, taking the 
candle, I entered the room and closed the door.

109
00:12:29,920 --> 00:12:37,840
The only piece of furniture in the large, dusty 
bedroom was a bed, placed next to the window.  

110
00:12:38,480 --> 00:12:44,880
There were heavy curtains which could be pulled 
around it, to hide the sleeper from anyone else  

111
00:12:44,880 --> 00:12:53,600
in the room. Looking inside the curtains I saw a 
little shelf full of books, just under the window.  

112
00:12:55,280 --> 00:13:03,760
I put my candle down on the shelf, and dropped 
thankfully on to the bed. I closed the curtains  

113
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:10,560
around the bed, and felt safe from Heathcliff 
and everyone else at Wuthering Heights.

114
00:13:13,680 --> 00:13:21,280
I noticed that there were names written on the 
wall in childish handwriting - Catherine Earnshaw,  

115
00:13:22,560 --> 00:13:26,080
Catherine Heathcliff and Catherine Linton.  

116
00:13:28,320 --> 00:13:37,360
Then I fell asleep, but I was woken very suddenly 
by a smell of burning. My candle had fallen on to  

117
00:13:37,360 --> 00:13:44,880
a Bible on the shelf and was burning it. When 
I opened the Bible to see if it was damaged,  

118
00:13:45,600 --> 00:13:52,160
I found that wherever there was an empty page, 
or half a page, someone had written on it,  

119
00:13:53,440 --> 00:14:01,840
and on the first page was written 
'Catherine Earnshaw's diary, 1776'.  

120
00:14:03,120 --> 00:14:08,160
Who was the girl who had slept in this 
bed, written her name on the wall,  

121
00:14:09,280 --> 00:14:17,520
and then written her diary in the Bible, 
twenty-five years ago? I read it with interest.

122
00:14:20,400 --> 00:14:27,920
'How I hate my brother Hindley!' it 
began. 'He is so cruel to poor Heathcliff.  

123
00:14:29,440 --> 00:14:37,120
If only my father hadn't died! While he 
was alive, Heathcliff was like a brother  

124
00:14:37,120 --> 00:14:45,840
to Hindley and me. But now Hindley and his wife 
Frances have inherited the house and the money,  

125
00:14:46,720 --> 00:14:54,800
and they hate Heathcliff. That horrible old 
servant Joseph is always angry with Heathcliff  

126
00:14:54,800 --> 00:14:59,200
and me because we don't pray or study the Bible,  

127
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:10,880
and when he tells his master, Hindley always 
punishes us. I can't stop crying. Poor Heathcliff!  

128
00:15:11,840 --> 00:15:17,680
Hindley says he is wicked, and can't 
play with me or eat with me anymore.'

129
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:26,240
My eyes were beginning to 
close again and I fell asleep.  

130
00:15:26,240 --> 00:15:32,960
Never before had I passed such a terrible 
night, disturbed by the most frightening dreams.  

131
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:42,080
Suddenly I was woken by a gentle knocking on 
the window. It must be the branch of a tree, I  

132
00:15:42,080 --> 00:15:49,440
thought, and tried to sleep again. Outside I could 
hear the wind driving the snow against the window.

133
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:57,360
But I could not sleep. The knocking annoyed 
me so much that I tried to open the window.  

134
00:15:59,120 --> 00:16:05,040
When it did not open, I broke the glass angrily 
and stretched out my hand towards the branch.  

135
00:16:06,880 --> 00:16:10,560
But instead, my fingers closed around a small,  

136
00:16:11,200 --> 00:16:22,560
ice-cold hand! It held my hand tightly, and 
a voice cried sadly, 'Let me in! Let me in!'

137
00:16:24,880 --> 00:16:29,760
'Who are you?' I asked, 
trying to pull my hand away.

138
00:16:31,760 --> 00:16:39,840
'Catherine Linton,' it replied. 
'I've come home. I lost my way!'  

139
00:16:42,320 --> 00:16:46,480
There seemed to be a child's 
face looking in at the window.

140
00:16:49,120 --> 00:16:54,080
Terror made me cruel. I rubbed 
the creature's tiny wrist  

141
00:16:54,080 --> 00:16:58,480
against the broken glass so that 
blood poured down on to the bed.  

142
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:07,520
As soon as the cold fingers let go for a moment, 
I pulled my hand quickly back, put a pile of  

143
00:17:07,520 --> 00:17:13,600
books in front of the broken window, and tried 
not to listen to the desperate cries outside.

144
00:17:15,920 --> 00:17:24,160
'Go away!' I called. 'I'll never let you in, 
not if you go on crying for twenty years!'

145
00:17:26,480 --> 00:17:32,160
'It is almost twenty years!' 
replied the sad little voice.  

146
00:17:33,840 --> 00:17:42,080
'I've been out here in the dark for nearly 
twenty years!' The hand started pushing through  

147
00:17:42,080 --> 00:17:47,840
the window at the pile of books, and I knew 
it would find me and catch hold of me again.  

148
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:59,840
Unable to move, I stared in horror at 
the shape behind the glass, and screamed.

149
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:02,640
There were rapid footsteps 
outside my bedroom door,  

150
00:18:03,360 --> 00:18:06,000
and then I saw the light of a candle in the room.

151
00:18:08,080 --> 00:18:15,760
'Is anyone here?' whispered Heathcliff. He 
could not see me behind the curtains, and  

152
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:23,920
clearly did not expect an answer. I knew I could 
not hide from him, so I opened the curtains wide.

153
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:32,560
I was surprised by the effect of my action. 
Heathcliff dropped his candle and stood  

154
00:18:32,560 --> 00:18:41,840
without moving, his face as white as the wall 
behind him. He did not seem to recognize me.

155
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:47,040
'It's only your guest, Lockwood,' I said.  

156
00:18:48,160 --> 00:18:53,120
'I'm sorry, I must have had a bad 
dream and screamed in my sleep.'

157
00:18:55,600 --> 00:18:58,720
'To the devil with you, Mr Lockwood!'  

158
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:07,040
growled my landlord. 'Who allowed you 
to steep in this room? Who was it?'

159
00:19:08,560 --> 00:19:13,920
'It was your housekeeper, Mr Heathcliff,' 
I said, quickly putting my clothes on.  

160
00:19:15,200 --> 00:19:20,880
'And I'm angry with her myself! No one 
can sleep in a room full of ghosts!'

161
00:19:23,600 --> 00:19:31,520
'What do you mean?' asked Heathcliff, looking 
suddenly very interested. 'Ghosts, you say?'

162
00:19:33,520 --> 00:19:41,040
'That little girl, Catherine Linton, or Earnshaw, 
or whatever her name was, must have been wicked!  

163
00:19:42,480 --> 00:19:46,080
She told me she had been a 
ghost for nearly twenty years.  

164
00:19:47,360 --> 00:19:50,000
It was probably a punishment for her wickedness!'

165
00:19:51,520 --> 00:19:57,920
'How dare you speak of her to 
me?' cried Heathcliff wildly.  

166
00:20:00,400 --> 00:20:03,920
But as I described my dream, he became calmer,  

167
00:20:04,720 --> 00:20:09,360
and sat down on the bed, trembling 
as he tried to control his feelings.

168
00:20:12,080 --> 00:20:17,360
'Mr Lockwood,' he said finally, 
brushing a tear from his eye,  

169
00:20:19,280 --> 00:20:28,160
'you can go into my bedroom to sleep for the 
rest of the night. I'll stay here for a while.'

170
00:20:30,960 --> 00:20:34,240
'No more sleep for me tonight,' I replied.  

171
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:42,480
'I'll wait in the kitchen until it's daylight, 
and then I'll leave. You needn't worry about  

172
00:20:42,480 --> 00:20:48,480
my visiting you again either. I've 
had enough company for a long time.'

173
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:58,400
But as I turned to go downstairs, my landlord, 
thinking he was alone, threw himself on the bed,  

174
00:20:58,960 --> 00:21:02,720
pushed open the window and 
called into the darkness.

175
00:21:04,560 --> 00:21:11,120
'Come in! Come in!' he cried, 
tears rolling down his face.  

176
00:21:12,960 --> 00:21:20,800
'Catherine, do come! My 
darling, hear me this time!'

177
00:21:23,440 --> 00:21:26,560
But only the snow and wind blew into the room.

178
00:21:28,960 --> 00:21:31,840
How could my dream have produced such madness?  

179
00:21:33,520 --> 00:21:37,840
I could not watch his suffering 
any more, and went downstairs.

180
00:21:40,720 --> 00:21:46,560
I waited in the kitchen until it was light enough 
outside for me to find my way through the deep  

181
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:55,840
snow back to Thrushcross Grange. The housekeeper 
there, Ellen Dean, rushed out to welcome me home.  

182
00:21:57,680 --> 00:22:00,960
She thought I must have died in 
the previous night's snowstorm.  

183
00:22:02,560 --> 00:22:11,840
With a warm fire, and a hot meal, I began 
to recover from my unpleasant experiences.

184
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:17,200
After my stay at Wuthering Heights, 
I thought I would never want to speak  

185
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:26,160
to any human being again, but by the end of 
the next day I was beginning to feel lonely.  

186
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:30,000
I decided to ask Mrs Dean 
to sit with me after supper.

187
00:22:32,720 --> 00:22:36,000
'How long have you lived in 
this house?' I asked her.

188
00:22:37,760 --> 00:22:48,240
'Eighteen years, sir. I came here early in 1783 
when my mistress was married, to look after her.  

189
00:22:49,600 --> 00:22:53,840
And when she died, I stayed here as housekeeper.'

190
00:22:55,840 --> 00:22:58,480
'Who was your mistress?' I asked.

191
00:23:00,480 --> 00:23:04,480
'Her name was Catherine Earnshaw,' she replied.

192
00:23:06,080 --> 00:23:12,240
'Ah, my ghostly Catherine,' 
I muttered quietly to myself.

193
00:23:14,800 --> 00:23:18,240
'She married Mr Edgar Linton, a neighbour,'  

194
00:23:19,200 --> 00:23:26,960
added Mrs Dean, 'and they had a daughter, 
Cathy, who married Mr Heathcliffs son.'

195
00:23:29,200 --> 00:23:35,840
'Ah, so that must be the widow, young 
Mrs Heathcliff at Wuthering Heights!'

196
00:23:37,120 --> 00:23:43,920
'That's right, sir. Did you see her? I 
looked after her as a baby, you know.  

197
00:23:45,280 --> 00:23:49,840
How is she? I do want to know.'

198
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:56,720
'She looked very well, and very 
beautiful. But I don't think she's happy.'

199
00:23:58,480 --> 00:24:04,320
'Oh, poor thing! And what did 
you think of Mr Heathcliff?'

200
00:24:06,320 --> 00:24:15,360
'He's a rough, hard man, Mrs Dean. But I'm very 
interested in him. Tell me more about him.'

201
00:24:17,120 --> 00:24:23,280
'Well, he's very rich, of course, 
and mean at the same time.  

202
00:24:24,800 --> 00:24:32,160
He could live here at Thrushcross Grange, which 
is a finer house than Wuthering Heights, but he  

203
00:24:32,160 --> 00:24:40,560
would rather receive rent than live comfortably. 
But I'll tell you the whole story of his life,  

204
00:24:41,520 --> 00:24:48,000
as much as I know, that is, and 
then you can judge for yourself.'
 
 

205
00:24:52,640 --> 00:24:53,520
CHAPTER THREE

206
00:24:54,560 --> 00:24:59,840
Ellen Dean's story - Catherine 
and Heathcliff as children

207
00:25:05,600 --> 00:25:12,560
When I was a child, I was always at Wuthering 
Heights, because my mother was a servant with  

208
00:25:12,560 --> 00:25:19,600
the Earnshaw family. They are a very old family 
who have lived in that house for centuries,  

209
00:25:20,320 --> 00:25:26,880
as you can see from their name on the 
stone over the front door. I grew up  

210
00:25:26,880 --> 00:25:32,160
with Catherine and Hindley Earnshaw, and 
we three played together as children.

211
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:41,360
One day, their father Mr Earnshaw came 
back from a long journey. He had travelled  

212
00:25:41,360 --> 00:25:46,320
sixty miles to Liverpool and back 
on business, and was very tired.

213
00:25:48,240 --> 00:25:54,080
'Look what I've brought you!' he told us all, 
unwrapping something he was holding carefully  

214
00:25:54,080 --> 00:26:01,360
in his arms. Catherine and Hindley were expecting 
presents, and they rushed eagerly to see what it  

215
00:26:01,360 --> 00:26:09,840
was. They were very disappointed to see 
only a dirty, black-haired gipsy child.

216
00:26:11,520 --> 00:26:16,160
'I found him all alone in the 
busy streets of Liverpool,'  

217
00:26:16,960 --> 00:26:24,320
Mr Earnshaw explained to them, and I couldn't 
leave him to die. He can sleep in your room.'  

218
00:26:25,920 --> 00:26:31,600
But Hindley and Catherine were angry 
because they had not received any presents,  

219
00:26:31,600 --> 00:26:38,880
and refused to let the strange child share 
their room. However Mr Earnshaw insisted,  

220
00:26:39,680 --> 00:26:46,320
and little by little the boy became 
accepted by the family. He was called  

221
00:26:46,320 --> 00:26:53,600
Heathcliff, as a first and last name. No one 
ever discovered who his parents had been.

222
00:26:55,600 --> 00:27:03,120
Catherine and he became great friends, but 
Hindley hated him, and was often cruel to him.  

223
00:27:04,320 --> 00:27:12,160
Old Mr Earnshaw was strangely fond of this 
gipsy child, and frequently punished his son for  

224
00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:20,320
behaving badly to Heathcliff. Hindley began to be 
jealous of his father's feelings for Heathcliff,  

225
00:27:20,320 --> 00:27:22,080
and saw them both as enemies.

226
00:27:23,440 --> 00:27:28,640
This situation could not last. 
As Mr Earnshaw grew old and ill,  

227
00:27:29,360 --> 00:27:35,920
Heathcliff became even more his favourite, 
and Hindley often quarrelled with his father.  

228
00:27:37,440 --> 00:27:44,400
When Hindley was sent away to study, I hoped 
that we would have peace in the house. But then  

229
00:27:44,400 --> 00:27:51,120
it was that old servant Joseph who caused 
trouble. He tried to persuade his master  

230
00:27:51,120 --> 00:27:57,600
to be stricter with the children, and was 
always complaining that Heathcliff and Catherine  

231
00:27:57,600 --> 00:28:02,560
did not spend enough time studying the 
Bible or attending church services.

232
00:28:04,080 --> 00:28:07,600
Catherine was a wild, wicked girl in those days.  

233
00:28:08,400 --> 00:28:15,280
We had to watch her every moment of the day, to 
stop her playing her tricks on us. She was proud,  

234
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:23,120
and liked giving orders. But she had the prettiest 
face and the sweetest smile you've ever seen.  

235
00:28:24,480 --> 00:28:27,840
I could forgive her anything when 
she came to say she was sorry.

236
00:28:29,360 --> 00:28:36,240
She was much too fond of Heathcliff, and the 
worst punishment we could invent was to keep  

237
00:28:36,240 --> 00:28:42,400
her separate from him. Her father could 
no longer understand her or her behaviour,  

238
00:28:43,120 --> 00:28:48,240
and Catherine did not realize that his 
illness made him less patient with her.

239
00:28:49,920 --> 00:28:59,920
At last Mr Earnshaw found peace. He died quietly 
in his chair by the fire one October evening in  

240
00:28:59,920 --> 00:29:09,040
1775. The night was wild and stormy, and we 
were all sitting together in the big kitchen.  

241
00:29:10,720 --> 00:29:17,440
Joseph was reading his Bible at the table, while 
Catherine had her head on her father's knee.  

242
00:29:18,720 --> 00:29:23,840
He was pleased to see her so gentle for 
once, and she was singing him to sleep.  

243
00:29:25,440 --> 00:29:28,240
I was glad the old gentleman was sleeping so well.  

244
00:29:29,440 --> 00:29:36,320
But when it was time to go to bed, Catherine put 
her arms round her father's neck to say goodnight,  

245
00:29:37,120 --> 00:29:43,760
and immediately screamed, 'Oh, 
he's dead, Heathcliff! He's dead!'

246
00:29:45,280 --> 00:29:50,000
Heathcliff and I started 
crying loudly and bitterly too.  

247
00:29:51,440 --> 00:29:58,480
Joseph told me to fetch the doctor, so I ran to 
the village, although I knew it was too late.  

248
00:30:00,560 --> 00:30:04,640
When I came back, I went to the children's room,  

249
00:30:04,640 --> 00:30:12,320
to see if they needed me, and I listened for 
a moment at their door. They were imagining  

250
00:30:12,320 --> 00:30:18,960
the dead man in a beautiful distant place, 
far from the troubles of this world.  

251
00:30:20,160 --> 00:30:28,160
And as I listened, crying silently, I could not 
help wishing we were all there safe together.
 
 

252
00:30:32,800 --> 00:30:33,520
CHAPTER FOUR

253
00:30:35,120 --> 00:30:38,160
Catherine Earnshaw gets to know the Lintons

254
00:30:39,680 --> 00:30:48,400
1775 Hindley came home for his father's burial.  

255
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:58,560
What was more surprising was that he brought a 
wife with him. She was called Frances, a thin,  

256
00:30:58,560 --> 00:31:05,600
pale woman with a frequent cough. Now 
that Hindley was the master of the house,  

257
00:31:06,320 --> 00:31:13,280
he ordered Joseph and me to spend our evenings in 
the small back-kitchen, as we were only servants,  

258
00:31:14,240 --> 00:31:21,600
while he, his wife and Catherine sat in the 
main room. Catherine and Heathcliff were  

259
00:31:21,600 --> 00:31:28,560
treated very differently. Catherine received 
presents, and could continue her lessons,  

260
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:36,480
but Heathcliff was made to work on the farm with 
the men, and, as a farm worker, was only allowed  

261
00:31:36,480 --> 00:31:45,440
to eat with us in the back-kitchen. They grew up 
like two wild animals. Hindley did not care what  

262
00:31:45,440 --> 00:31:54,000
they did, as long as they kept out of his way, and 
they did not care even if he punished them. They  

263
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:01,360
often ran away on to the moors in the morning and 
stayed out all day, just to make Hindley angry.  

264
00:32:02,720 --> 00:32:09,440
I was the only one who cared what happened to the 
two poor creatures, and I was afraid for them.

265
00:32:11,280 --> 00:32:18,880
One Sunday evening they were missing at bedtime, 
and Hindley ordered me angrily to lock the front  

266
00:32:18,880 --> 00:32:27,200
door. But I did not want them to stay out in the 
cold all night, so I kept my window open to look  

267
00:32:27,200 --> 00:32:36,080
out for them. In a while I saw Heathcliff walking 
through the gate. I was shocked to see him alone.

268
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:40,160
'Where's Catherine?' I cried sharply.

269
00:32:41,400 --> 00:32:49,120
'At Thrushcross Grange, with our neighbor's the 
Lintons,' he replied. Let me in, Ellen, and I'll  

270
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:57,200
explain what happened.' I went down to unlock 
the door, and we came upstairs very quietly.

271
00:32:58,320 --> 00:33:02,880
'Don't wake the master up!' 
I whispered. 'Now tell me!'

272
00:33:04,480 --> 00:33:11,200
'Well, Catherine and I thought we'd just 
walk to the Lintons' house. We wanted to  

273
00:33:11,200 --> 00:33:17,920
see if Isabella and Edgar Linton are punished 
all the time by their parents, as we are.'

274
00:33:19,280 --> 00:33:25,360
'Probably not,' I answered. 'I expect they are 
good children and don't need to be punished.'

275
00:33:26,880 --> 00:33:35,360
'Nonsense, Ellen! Guess what we saw when we looked 
in at their sitting-room window? A very pretty  

276
00:33:35,360 --> 00:33:43,040
room, with soft carpets and white walls. Catherine 
and I would love to have a room like that!  

277
00:33:44,160 --> 00:33:51,840
But in the middle of this beautiful room, Isabella 
and Edgar Linton were screaming and fighting  

278
00:33:52,480 --> 00:34:01,600
over a little dog! How stupid they are, Ellen! 
If Catherine wanted something, I would give it  

279
00:34:01,600 --> 00:34:09,200
to her, and she would do the same for me. I would 
rather be here at Wuthering Heights with her, even  

280
00:34:09,200 --> 00:34:16,400
if I'm punished by Joseph and that wicked Hindley, 
than at Thrushcross Grange with those two fools!'

281
00:34:17,600 --> 00:34:24,160
'Not so loud, Heathcliff! But you still 
haven't told me why Catherine isn't with you?'

282
00:34:26,160 --> 00:34:35,440
'Well, as we were looking in, we started laughing 
at them so loudly that they heard us, and sent the  

283
00:34:35,440 --> 00:34:44,560
dogs after us. We were about to run away, when 
a great fierce dog caught Catherine's leg in its  

284
00:34:44,560 --> 00:34:52,480
teeth. I attacked it, and made it let go of 
her leg, but the Lintons' servants appeared  

285
00:34:52,480 --> 00:34:59,840
and caught hold of me. They must have thought we 
were robbers. Catherine was carried unconscious  

286
00:34:59,840 --> 00:35:06,960
into the house, and they pulled me inside too. 
All the time I was shouting and swearing at them.

287
00:35:08,480 --> 00:35:16,080
"What a wicked pair of thieves!" said 
old Mr Linton. "The boy must be a gipsy,  

288
00:35:16,080 --> 00:35:22,320
he's as dark as the devil!" 
Mrs Linton raised her hands in  

289
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:29,840
horror at the sight of me. Catherine opened 
her eyes, and Edgar looked closely at her.

290
00:35:31,200 --> 00:35:40,320
"Mother," he whispered, "the young lady is Miss 
Earnshaw, of Wuthering Heights. I've seen her in  

291
00:35:40,320 --> 00:35:46,640
church occasionally. And look what our dog 
has done to her leg! It's bleeding badly!"

292
00:35:48,640 --> 00:35:57,840
"Miss Earnshaw with a gipsy!" cried Mrs Linton. 
"Surely not! But I think you must be right, Edgar.  

293
00:35:58,880 --> 00:36:06,160
This girl is wearing black, and Mr 
Earnshaw died recently. It must be her.  

294
00:36:07,520 --> 00:36:12,320
I'd better put a bandage on her leg at once."

295
00:36:12,320 --> 00:36:19,600
"Why does her brother Hindley let her run around 
with such a companion?" wondered Mr Linton. "I  

296
00:36:19,600 --> 00:36:27,040
remember now, he's the gipsy child Mr Earnshaw 
brought home from Liverpool a few years ago."

297
00:36:28,480 --> 00:36:32,640
"He's a wicked boy, you can 
see that," said Mrs Linton.  

298
00:36:33,360 --> 00:36:39,840
"And did you hear the bad language he used just 
now? I'm shocked that my children heard it."

299
00:36:41,200 --> 00:36:48,960
I was pushed out into the garden, but I stayed to 
watch through the window. They put Catherine on a  

300
00:36:48,960 --> 00:36:57,440
comfortable sofa, cleaned her wound and fed her 
with cakes and wine. I only left the house when  

301
00:36:57,440 --> 00:37:04,720
I was sure she was well taken care of. She's a 
breath of fresh air for those stupid Lintons.

302
00:37:04,720 --> 00:37:11,120
'I'm not surprised they like her. Everybody who 
sees her must love her, mustn't they, Ellen?'

303
00:37:12,960 --> 00:37:18,080
'I'm afraid you'll be punished for 
this, Heathcliff,' I said sadly.

304
00:37:18,960 --> 00:37:24,320
And I was right. Hindley warned 
Heathcliff that he must never  

305
00:37:24,320 --> 00:37:28,400
speak to Catherine again, or he would 
be sent away from Wuthering Heights,  

306
00:37:29,200 --> 00:37:36,160
and it was decided that Catherine would 
be taught to behave like a young lady.

307
00:37:36,160 --> 00:37:44,960
She stayed with the Linton family at Thrushcross 
Grange for five weeks, until Christmas. By that  

308
00:37:44,960 --> 00:37:54,160
time her leg was fine, and her manners were much 
better than before. Frances Earnshaw visited her  

309
00:37:54,160 --> 00:38:00,880
often, bringing her pretty dresses to wear, and 
persuading her to take care of her appearance,  

310
00:38:01,600 --> 00:38:08,320
so that when she finally came home after her long 
absence, she almost seemed a different person.  

311
00:38:09,440 --> 00:38:16,160
Instead of a wild, hatless girl, we saw a 
beautiful, carefully dressed young lady.

312
00:38:17,600 --> 00:38:20,720
When she had greeted all of 
us, she asked for Heathcliff.

313
00:38:22,560 --> 00:38:25,680
'Come forward, Heathcliff!' called Hindley.  

314
00:38:26,480 --> 00:38:32,160
You may welcome Miss Catherine 
home, like the other servants.'

315
00:38:32,160 --> 00:38:38,000
Heathcliff was used to being outside all day, and 
had not bothered to wash or change his clothes.  

316
00:38:38,800 --> 00:38:41,440
His face and hands were black with dirt.  

317
00:38:42,480 --> 00:38:49,840
In spite of this, Catherine was very glad to see 
him and rushed up to kiss him. Then she laughed.

318
00:38:51,360 --> 00:38:59,760
'How funny and black and cross you look! But 
that's because I'm used to Edgar and Isabella,  

319
00:38:59,760 --> 00:39:05,760
who are always so clean and tidy. Well, 
Heathcliff, have you forgotten me?'

320
00:39:07,360 --> 00:39:15,200
But, ashamed and proud, the boy said nothing, 
until suddenly his feelings were too much for him.

321
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:20,080
'I won't stay to be laughed at!' he cried,  

322
00:39:20,640 --> 00:39:24,720
and was about to run away, when 
Catherine caught hold of his hand.

323
00:39:26,400 --> 00:39:35,600
'Why are you angry, Heathcliff? You... you just 
look a bit strange, that's all. You're so dirty!'

324
00:39:37,280 --> 00:39:42,000
She looked worriedly at her 
hands, and her new dress.

325
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:44,640
'You needn't have touched me!' he said,  

326
00:39:45,280 --> 00:39:50,800
pulling away his hand. 'I like being 
dirty, and I'm going to be dirty!'

327
00:39:52,560 --> 00:39:58,480
As he ran miserably out of the room, 
Hindley and his wife laughed loudly,  

328
00:39:59,040 --> 00:40:04,640
delighted that their plan to separate the 
two young people seemed to be succeeding.

329
00:40:06,320 --> 00:40:13,440
The next day was Christmas Day. Edgar and 
Isabella Linton had been invited to lunch,  

330
00:40:14,160 --> 00:40:21,600
and their mother had agreed, on condition that 
her darlings were kept carefully apart from that  

331
00:40:21,600 --> 00:40:26,240
wicked boy. I felt sorry for poor Heathcliff,  

332
00:40:26,800 --> 00:40:32,640
and while the Earnshaws were at church, I 
helped him wash and dress in clean clothes.

333
00:40:34,160 --> 00:40:40,880
'You're too proud,' I scolded him as I 
brushed his black hair. You should think  

334
00:40:40,880 --> 00:40:47,440
how sad Catherine is when you can't be 
together. And don't be jealous of Edgar Linton!'

335
00:40:49,520 --> 00:40:53,360
'I wish I had blue eyes and fair hair like him!  

336
00:40:54,480 --> 00:40:58,480
I wish I behaved well, and was 
going to inherit a fortune!'

337
00:41:00,320 --> 00:41:03,840
'He has none of your intelligence or character!  

338
00:41:04,560 --> 00:41:08,000
And if you have a good heart, 
you'll have a handsome face.  

339
00:41:09,040 --> 00:41:16,400
Who knows who your parents were? Perhaps a king 
and queen, far more important than the Lintons!'

340
00:41:18,400 --> 00:41:25,920
In this way I encouraged Heathcliff to have more 
confidence in himself. But when the Earnshaws  

341
00:41:25,920 --> 00:41:33,920
and the Lintons arrived back from church, the 
first thing Hindley did was shout at Heathcliff.

342
00:41:33,920 --> 00:41:37,840
'Get out of my sight, until we've finished eating!  

343
00:41:39,040 --> 00:41:42,400
I'll pull that long hair of yours 
if you don't obey me at once!'

344
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:52,480
'It is long,' said Edgar. I'm surprised he can 
see anything.' This was too much for Heathcliff.  

345
00:41:53,360 --> 00:42:00,560
He looked desperately around for a weapon, picked 
up a bowl of hot soup and threw it at Edgar,  

346
00:42:00,560 --> 00:42:07,600
who started screaming. Hindley immediately took 
hold of Heathcliff and pushed him upstairs.

347
00:42:09,200 --> 00:42:16,400
'I'm sure Hindley's going to hit him!' 
cried Catherine. 'I hate it when Heathcliff  

348
00:42:16,400 --> 00:42:23,040
is punished! It's your fault, Edgar, you 
annoyed him! Why did you speak to him?'

349
00:42:25,040 --> 00:42:30,320
'I didn't,' replied Edgar, tears in his eyes. 'I  

350
00:42:30,320 --> 00:42:36,240
promised Mother I wouldn't. I 
spoke about him, not to him.'

351
00:42:37,680 --> 00:42:41,280
'Well, don't cry,' said Catherine with scorn.  

352
00:42:41,840 --> 00:42:45,440
'You've made enough trouble 
already. Here comes my brother.'

353
00:42:46,960 --> 00:42:49,920
Hindley returned, hot and breathless.

354
00:42:50,960 --> 00:42:55,360
'That'll teach him!' he said. 
'And now let's have lunch!'

355
00:42:56,560 --> 00:43:02,800
The others seemed to forget Heathcliff, 
but I noticed Catherine could not eat much,  

356
00:43:03,360 --> 00:43:11,520
and I knew she was sorry for her friend. In the 
evening there was music from a travelling band,  

357
00:43:11,520 --> 00:43:18,000
and dancing in the main room. Catherine 
said the music sounded sweeter from high up,  

358
00:43:18,640 --> 00:43:26,720
and so she went to sit in the dark on the stairs. 
When I went to find her, however, I discovered  

359
00:43:26,720 --> 00:43:32,240
she had gone right to the top of the house to talk 
to Heathcliff through his locked bedroom door,  

360
00:43:33,040 --> 00:43:39,840
and had then climbed out on to the roof and 
in through his window. I persuaded them both  

361
00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:47,760
to come out of the room the same way, as I had 
no key to the door, and took Heathcliff down  

362
00:43:47,760 --> 00:43:54,400
into the warm servants' kitchen with me, while 
Catherine returned to her guests and the dancing.

363
00:43:55,760 --> 00:43:58,320
'You must be hungry, Heathcliff,' I said.  

364
00:43:59,040 --> 00:44:03,120
'You haven't eaten all day. 
Have some Christmas cake, do.'

365
00:44:04,960 --> 00:44:10,000
'I can't eat anything,' he growled, 
putting his head in his hands.  

366
00:44:11,360 --> 00:44:18,720
'I've got to think how I can have my revenge 
on Hindley. I only hope he doesn't die first!  

367
00:44:19,680 --> 00:44:22,960
He'll be sorry he's treated 
me like this, Ellen!'
 
 

368
00:44:27,440 --> 00:44:28,320
CHAPTER FIVE

369
00:44:29,200 --> 00:44:30,480
Catherine and Edgar

370
00:44:31,440 --> 00:44:41,920
1778 In the summer of this year Hindley's 
wife Frances had her first, and last,  

371
00:44:41,920 --> 00:44:49,840
baby. They called the boy Hareton. But the 
poor woman had been ill for a long time,  

372
00:44:49,840 --> 00:44:54,800
although we had not realized it, and 
died soon after Hareton was born.

373
00:44:56,400 --> 00:45:05,680
Hindley only had room in his heart for two 
people, himself and his wife, so when she died,  

374
00:45:05,680 --> 00:45:14,560
he was in despair. He neither cried nor 
prayed. Instead he swore at God and man, and  

375
00:45:14,560 --> 00:45:24,320
drank himself to sleep every night. The servants 
all left him, except for Joseph and me. Joseph  

376
00:45:24,320 --> 00:45:29,200
enjoyed being able to scold his wicked 
employer, with warnings from the Bible,  

377
00:45:29,920 --> 00:45:35,760
and I could not leave Miss Catherine. After 
all, I had grown up with her and Hindley.

378
00:45:37,200 --> 00:45:43,440
But the master's behaviour was a bad example 
for Catherine and Heathcliff. At fifteen,  

379
00:45:44,160 --> 00:45:50,560
Catherine was the most beautiful girl for miles 
around, but she was proud and quick-tempered.  

380
00:45:51,600 --> 00:45:59,520
She led what was almost a double life. At 
Wuthering Heights, under Heathcliffs influence,  

381
00:45:59,520 --> 00:46:06,720
she annoyed Hindley, laughed at Joseph, and 
was rude to me. But at Thrushcross Grange,  

382
00:46:06,720 --> 00:46:13,760
which she often visited, she showed a different, 
calmer side of her character, and was polite,  

383
00:46:13,760 --> 00:46:21,680
intelligent and amusing. The Lintons all liked 
her, and poor Edgar had fallen in love with her.

384
00:46:23,520 --> 00:46:30,080
Heathcliff was sixteen at this time. He did 
not have time to study any more, and the long  

385
00:46:30,080 --> 00:46:37,840
hours of work on the farm made him tired and dull. 
There was always an angry expression on his face,  

386
00:46:38,560 --> 00:46:45,840
and he did not even try to keep himself clean and 
tidy. He seemed to want people to dislike him.  

387
00:46:47,600 --> 00:46:54,640
Catherine and he still spent time together, when 
he was not working in the fields, but he no longer  

388
00:46:54,640 --> 00:47:00,720
expressed his fondness for her in words, and 
he looked angry if she touched or kissed him.

389
00:47:02,320 --> 00:47:05,760
One afternoon, when Hindley had gone into town,  

390
00:47:06,640 --> 00:47:13,040
Heathcliff came into the main room after lunch. 
I was helping Catherine to arrange her hair,  

391
00:47:13,680 --> 00:47:18,480
as she had invited Edgar Linton to 
visit her while Hindley was absent.

392
00:47:20,640 --> 00:47:23,840
'Catherine, are you going 
anywhere this afternoon?'  

393
00:47:24,720 --> 00:47:31,280
asked Heathcliff. 'Why have you got that silk 
dress on? Nobody's visiting you, I hope.'

394
00:47:33,280 --> 00:47:37,360
'No-o, I don't think so,' replied Catherine,  

395
00:47:37,360 --> 00:47:41,680
looking quickly at me. 'But you 
should be at work by now, Heathcliff.'

396
00:47:42,880 --> 00:47:50,240
'That devil Hindley isn't away very often. I'm 
taking a holiday. I won't work anymore today.  

397
00:47:51,200 --> 00:47:54,400
I'm staying with you this 
afternoon. He'll never know.'

398
00:47:56,240 --> 00:48:05,600
Catherine thought for a moment. 'Somehow she had 
to prepare him for Edgar's visit. Isabella and  

399
00:48:05,600 --> 00:48:12,640
Edgar said they might call here this afternoon. 
If they come, you'll be scolded for not working.'

400
00:48:14,400 --> 00:48:20,240
'Tell Ellen to say you're busy and can't 
see them,' he said. Those friends of yours  

401
00:48:20,240 --> 00:48:25,120
take up all your time. You spend most of 
your evenings with them, not with me.'

402
00:48:27,080 --> 00:48:31,840
'Well, why should I always spend my 
time with you?' she asked crossly.  

403
00:48:32,480 --> 00:48:35,920
'What can you talk about? How can you amuse me?'

404
00:48:37,760 --> 00:48:43,200
'You never told me before that you didn't 
like my company, Catherine!' cried Heathcliff.

405
00:48:44,640 --> 00:48:52,480
Just then we heard a horse outside, and there was 
a light knock on the door. Edgar Linton entered,  

406
00:48:53,120 --> 00:48:58,720
his handsome face full of delight at 
receiving Catherine's unexpected invitation.  

407
00:49:00,080 --> 00:49:06,560
I wondered if Catherine was comparing her two 
friends, as Edgar came in and Heathcliff ran out.

408
00:49:08,400 --> 00:49:13,440
'I haven't come too soon, 
have I?' asked Edgar politely.

409
00:49:14,320 --> 00:49:18,800
'No,' answered Catherine. 'Leave us alone, Ellen.'

410
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:25,200
'I'm just doing my work, miss,' I 
replied, pretending to dust the furniture.  

411
00:49:26,480 --> 00:49:31,440
'Hindley had told me to be present if 
Edgar Linton came to visit Catherine.'

412
00:49:32,800 --> 00:49:35,680
She came up to me, and whispered crossly,  

413
00:49:36,640 --> 00:49:43,840
'Go away, Ellen!' Keeping her back to 
Edgar, she cruelly scratched my arm.

414
00:49:44,640 --> 00:49:48,480
'Oh!' I screamed, to show Edgar what had happened.  

415
00:49:49,200 --> 00:49:53,520
'What a wicked thing to do, miss! 
You have no right to hurt me!'

416
00:49:55,120 --> 00:49:58,400
'I didn't touch you, you lying creature!'  

417
00:49:59,040 --> 00:50:04,960
she cried angrily, and, unable to 
control herself, hit me hard on the face.

418
00:50:06,720 --> 00:50:11,840
'Catherine, love! Catherine!' 
cried Edgar, shocked.

419
00:50:12,560 --> 00:50:15,840
The baby, Hareton, who followed me everywhere,  

420
00:50:15,840 --> 00:50:20,720
immediately started sobbing and 
saying, 'Wicked aunt Catherine!'

421
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:29,600
She picked him up and shook the poor child 
until he screamed. Edgar rushed up to her  

422
00:50:29,600 --> 00:50:37,680
and tried to stop her. At once she turned and 
hit him over the ear as hard as she could.

423
00:50:38,960 --> 00:50:43,360
The young man looked very pale 
and went straight to the door.

424
00:50:44,880 --> 00:50:53,840
'Where are you going, Edgar Linton?' she asked. 
'Don't leave me! I shall be miserable all night!'

425
00:50:55,200 --> 00:50:58,720
'Can I stay after you have hit me?'  

426
00:50:59,360 --> 00:51:06,160
he replied. 'You've made me afraid and 
ashamed of you. I won't come here again!'

427
00:51:07,680 --> 00:51:14,800
'Well, go then, if you want to!' she 
cried. 'I'm going to cry until I'm ill!'  

428
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:22,640
and she dropped on to the floor, her shoulders 
shaking and the tears rolling down her face.

429
00:51:24,160 --> 00:51:26,560
Edgar managed to get as far as the door.  

430
00:51:27,360 --> 00:51:33,280
But here he hesitated, and I called 
out to him to encourage him to leave.

431
00:51:34,640 --> 00:51:40,320
'Miss is just a selfish child, sir! 
You'd better ride home and forget her!'

432
00:51:41,760 --> 00:51:49,440
But as he could not stop looking at her, I knew 
there was no hope for him. Nothing would keep  

433
00:51:49,440 --> 00:51:58,160
him away from her now. And sure enough, he came 
back into the room and shut the door. This time  

434
00:51:58,880 --> 00:52:05,600
I left them alone, and stayed in the kitchen with 
little Hareton, but when I came to warn them that  

435
00:52:05,600 --> 00:52:12,720
Hindley had returned, I realized that their 
quarrel had only brought them closer together.

436
00:52:17,200 --> 00:52:18,160
CHAPTER SIX

437
00:52:19,360 --> 00:52:20,880
Heathcliff disappears

438
00:52:22,080 --> 00:52:30,880
1778-9 Hindley came into the kitchen, swearing  

439
00:52:30,880 --> 00:52:38,080
terribly, just as I was about to hide little 
Hareton in a cupboard. I was always afraid  

440
00:52:38,080 --> 00:52:46,080
that Hindley would hurt his small son, either 
by accident or on purpose, when he was drunk,  

441
00:52:46,080 --> 00:52:53,680
so I tried to keep Hareton out of the way. 
But this time Hindley discovered my plan.

442
00:52:55,280 --> 00:53:04,640
'Ah, you keep my son in a cupboard, do you!' he 
cried angrily, picking up a sharp kitchen knife.  

443
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:13,840
'With the devil's help I'll make you swallow this, 
Ellen!' And he pushed the knife between my teeth.

444
00:53:15,360 --> 00:53:22,080
I was never afraid he would hurt me, and 
calmly took the knife out of my mouth.

445
00:53:24,160 --> 00:53:30,720
'But that can't be my son, can 
it?' he continued aggressively,  

446
00:53:31,360 --> 00:53:39,920
staring at the frightened little boy. 'If it 
is, he should be punished for not running to  

447
00:53:39,920 --> 00:53:48,400
greet his father. Perhaps I'll cut his ears 
off!' And then suddenly his manner changed.

448
00:53:49,680 --> 00:53:58,960
'No, Hareton, darling, don't 
cry! Kiss me, kiss your father!  

449
00:54:00,640 --> 00:54:06,240
What? You won't? Then I'll break your neck!'

450
00:54:07,840 --> 00:54:13,520
Poor Hareton, screaming wildly, 
was carried upstairs by his father.  

451
00:54:14,960 --> 00:54:21,760
Suddenly Hindley stopped on the stairs to 
listen, almost forgetting what he was holding.  

452
00:54:23,200 --> 00:54:29,280
Heathcliff had come into the house and stood 
at the bottom of the stairs, looking up.  

453
00:54:30,480 --> 00:54:35,760
Just then the child jumped out 
of Hindley's arms and fell.  

454
00:54:36,960 --> 00:54:43,360
I only had time to gasp in horror, before 
I saw that Heathcliff had caught him.

455
00:54:45,200 --> 00:54:48,720
Heathcliff stared down at 
the child he was holding.  

456
00:54:49,840 --> 00:54:53,600
He must have felt sorry he had 
saved the life of his enemy's son.  

457
00:54:55,280 --> 00:55:01,840
I rushed to take the poor little boy in my 
arms, and Hindley came slowly downstairs.

458
00:55:03,520 --> 00:55:10,640
'Look what you've done, Mr Hindley!' I 
cried. 'You nearly killed your own son!  

459
00:55:12,160 --> 00:55:14,480
What would his mother say if she were alive?'

460
00:55:16,880 --> 00:55:26,800
'Take him away, Ellen. And you, Heathcliff, go 
away too. I won't murder you tonight, unless  

461
00:55:26,800 --> 00:55:35,440
perhaps I set the house on fire. But that depends 
how I feel.' And he poured himself a drink.

462
00:55:36,880 --> 00:55:40,480
'Don't drink any more, Mr Hindley!' I begged.

463
00:55:41,440 --> 00:55:50,080
'What difference does it make?' he growled. 
'Get out, both of you! To the devil with you!'

464
00:55:51,840 --> 00:55:55,920
We left him swearing at us, 
and went back into the kitchen.

465
00:55:57,360 --> 00:56:00,560
'It's a pity he can't kill himself with drink,'  

466
00:56:00,560 --> 00:56:06,800
muttered Heathcliff. Dr Kenneth says he'll 
live longer than any of us, he's so strong.'

467
00:56:08,640 --> 00:56:17,520
He walked out of the door and, I thought, into 
the fields. In fact I discovered later that he  

468
00:56:17,520 --> 00:56:23,360
was sitting just under the window, and could 
hear everything that was said in the kitchen.

469
00:56:24,880 --> 00:56:29,840
I was singing little Hareton to 
sleep when Catherine came in.

470
00:56:30,960 --> 00:56:35,520
'Are you alone, Ellen?' she 
whispered. 'Where's Heathcliff?'

471
00:56:36,960 --> 00:56:39,040
'He's out on the farm,' I answered.

472
00:56:40,320 --> 00:56:45,120
She looked sad and worried, and I 
even saw a tear or two on her face.  

473
00:56:46,160 --> 00:56:53,360
But I had not forgotten how she had lied, and 
behaved so badly to me as well as to Edgar Linton,  

474
00:56:53,360 --> 00:56:57,840
so I did not feel sorry for 
her, or encourage her to talk.

475
00:56:59,440 --> 00:57:07,520
'Ellen, will you keep a secret for me?' she 
asked in the end, giving me her sweetest smile.  

476
00:57:08,880 --> 00:57:12,720
'I must tell you! I need your advice.  

477
00:57:15,040 --> 00:57:22,080
Today Edgar Linton has asked me to 
marry him, and I gave him an answer.  

478
00:57:23,440 --> 00:57:30,480
Now, before I tell you if it was yes or 
no, you tell me which I should have said.'

479
00:57:32,400 --> 00:57:40,240
'Really, Miss Catherine, how can I know? 
Perhaps you should have refused him. He must  

480
00:57:40,240 --> 00:57:44,480
be a fool to ask you, after you were 
so rude and violent this afternoon.'

481
00:57:46,160 --> 00:57:49,680
'Well, I accepted him, Ellen!' she said crossly.  

482
00:57:50,400 --> 00:57:54,640
But should I have done so? 
Should I? What do you think?'

483
00:57:56,640 --> 00:58:00,000
'First, do you love him?' I asked.

484
00:58:01,040 --> 00:58:04,000
'Of course I do,' she replied.

485
00:58:05,760 --> 00:58:07,840
'Why do you love him, Miss Catherine?'

486
00:58:09,520 --> 00:58:17,920
'Well, I do, that's enough. Well, because 
he's handsome, and a pleasant companion.'

487
00:58:19,240 --> 00:58:23,040
'Oh, that's bad,' I said, shaking my head.

488
00:58:24,240 --> 00:58:25,680
'And because he loves me.'

489
00:58:26,640 --> 00:58:27,920
'That's worse.'

490
00:58:29,360 --> 00:58:35,840
'And because he'll be rich, and I shall be 
the most important woman for miles around.'

491
00:58:37,120 --> 00:58:41,680
'Worst of all. But there are several other  

492
00:58:41,680 --> 00:58:46,080
handsome, rich young men in the world. 
Why don't you marry one of them?'

493
00:58:47,600 --> 00:58:50,880
'I don't know any of them. I only know Edgar.'

494
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:59,360
'Well, I don't know why you're unhappy, Miss 
Catherine. Your brother will be pleased,  

495
00:58:59,360 --> 00:59:06,400
and Mr Edgar's parents will, too. You love 
Edgar, and Edgar loves you. What's the problem?'

496
00:59:08,160 --> 00:59:19,120
'Here! And here! replied Catherine, beating 
her head and her chest. 'In my heart and soul  

497
00:59:19,120 --> 00:59:28,720
I know I'm wrong! Ellen, I can't live apart 
from Heathcliff! He is more myself than I am.  

498
00:59:29,680 --> 00:59:38,000
Our souls are the same! I have nothing in common 
with Edgar. But I can't marry Heathcliff now!  

499
00:59:39,200 --> 00:59:45,840
Hindley has made him become a poor, dull farm 
worker. He'll never know how I love him.'

500
00:59:47,680 --> 00:59:54,720
I suddenly heard a movement outside the window, 
and saw Heathcliff stand up and walk away.  

501
00:59:55,920 --> 01:00:01,760
I realized he had been listening until he 
heard Catherine say she could not marry him.  

502
01:00:02,800 --> 01:00:04,880
Then he stayed to hear no more.

503
01:00:06,080 --> 01:00:13,200
'Quiet, Miss Catherine!' I said. Just 
imagine how hard it will be for Heathcliff  

504
01:00:13,200 --> 01:00:18,560
when you marry Mr Edgar! He'll have 
no friends at all when you leave him.'

505
01:00:20,080 --> 01:00:28,160
'Leave him? Why should we be separated?' 
she asked angrily. 'Who will separate us?  

506
01:00:28,160 --> 01:00:34,080
Nobody will dare! Edgar must 
learn to accept him as my friend.  

507
01:00:35,440 --> 01:00:39,600
Didn't you ever think, Ellen, 
that if Heathcliff and I married,  

508
01:00:39,600 --> 01:00:47,440
we would be very poor? But if I marry Edgar, I 
can help Heathcliff with my husband's money.'

509
01:00:49,120 --> 01:00:56,800
'That's the worst reason you've given so far 
for marrying Mr Edgar,' I replied, shocked.

510
01:00:57,920 --> 01:01:02,720
'It isn't! Heathcliff is more 
important to me than myself.  

511
01:01:04,080 --> 01:01:11,200
My love for Edgar is like the leaves on 
the trees. I'm sure time will change it.  

512
01:01:12,400 --> 01:01:19,520
But my love for Heathcliff is like the 
rocks in the ground - not beautiful,  

513
01:01:20,240 --> 01:01:27,360
but necessary and unchanging. 
He's always, always in my heart-'

514
01:01:29,200 --> 01:01:32,080
Just then Joseph entered the kitchen.  

515
01:01:33,520 --> 01:01:39,440
I whispered to Catherine that I was sure 
Heathcliff had heard some of what she said.  

516
01:01:40,640 --> 01:01:48,560
She jumped up, frightened, and rushed outside. But 
although we all looked everywhere for Heathcliff,  

517
01:01:49,120 --> 01:01:54,240
there was no sign of him that night, 
or for many nights in the future.

518
01:01:56,480 --> 01:02:04,080
At about midnight, while we were still waiting for 
him to come home, we noticed the wind was getting  

519
01:02:04,080 --> 01:02:10,960
stronger. We could hear it whistling down the 
chimney, and howling all around the house.  

520
01:02:12,240 --> 01:02:19,840
Suddenly there was a terrible crash of thunder, 
and the branch of a tree fell on to the roof.  

521
01:02:20,720 --> 01:02:26,560
We were not hurt, but Joseph immediately 
dropped on to his knees to pray.  

522
01:02:27,920 --> 01:02:30,720
The rain was beating down on the windows,  

523
01:02:31,520 --> 01:02:38,720
but Catherine stayed outside, although by 
now her hair and clothes were completely wet.

524
01:02:40,480 --> 01:02:46,400
In the end we all went to bed. I managed 
to persuade Catherine to come in,  

525
01:02:47,120 --> 01:02:53,120
but she insisted on sleeping in the kitchen, 
in case Heathcliff returned during the night.  

526
01:02:54,400 --> 01:03:02,880
In the morning we discovered that she had caught 
a fever, as a result of getting wet. She became  

527
01:03:02,880 --> 01:03:09,280
seriously ill, and it was several weeks 
before Dr Kenneth would allow her out of bed.

528
01:03:11,120 --> 01:03:19,360
When she recovered, she was invited to stay for 
a while at Thrushcross Grange. Unfortunately  

529
01:03:19,920 --> 01:03:28,320
old Mr and Mrs Linton caught the fever too, and 
died within a few days of each other. Catherine  

530
01:03:28,320 --> 01:03:35,120
returned to us, prouder and quicker-tempered 
than ever, but not as strong as before.

531
01:03:37,280 --> 01:03:45,440
'If she gets ill again, it could be fatal,' 
Dr Kenneth warned us. 'My advice to you  

532
01:03:45,440 --> 01:03:52,560
is to do whatever she wants, and don't 
make her angry!' So we had to obey  

533
01:03:52,560 --> 01:03:57,840
all her orders, and Joseph and I were 
not allowed to scold her any more.

534
01:03:59,200 --> 01:04:06,240
Edgar Linton was still in love with her, and 
thought himself the happiest man on earth when he  

535
01:04:06,240 --> 01:04:13,840
married her three years after his parents' death. 
She insisted on having me with her, so we moved  

536
01:04:13,840 --> 01:04:20,640
together to Thrushcross Grange, although I was 
very sad to leave little Hareton with his father.

537
01:04:22,560 --> 01:04:26,240
It's very late, Mr Lockwood. 
I think you should go to bed,  

538
01:04:26,240 --> 01:04:30,880
or you'll be ill tomorrow. I can tell 
you the rest of the story another time.

539
01:04:34,080 --> 01:04:44,560
Four weeks later in fact I was ill the next day, 
and have been ill since then. The terrible night  

540
01:04:44,560 --> 01:04:51,280
I spent at Wuthering Heights was the cause of 
my illness, and I blame Mr Heathcliff for it.  

541
01:04:53,200 --> 01:04:57,440
Dr Kenneth has warned me I won't 
be able to go out until the spring.  

542
01:04:59,040 --> 01:05:07,840
All I can do is lie in bed, listening to the 
howling wind and staring at the grey northern sky.

543
01:05:10,160 --> 01:05:16,560
So I've decided to ask Mrs Dean to come 
upstairs and finish telling me her story.  

544
01:05:18,320 --> 01:05:21,840
She tells me she's happy to continue.

545
01:05:26,320 --> 01:05:27,120
CHAPTER SEVEN

546
01:05:28,080 --> 01:05:29,440
Heathcliff returns

547
01:05:30,480 --> 01:05:42,640
1783 Well, sir, when Miss Catherine became Mrs 
Linton, and we went to live at Thrushcross Grange,  

548
01:05:43,440 --> 01:05:47,840
I must say I was surprised 
and pleased by her behaviour.  

549
01:05:48,800 --> 01:05:53,920
She showed great fondness for her 
husband, and for his sister, Isabella.  

550
01:05:55,200 --> 01:06:02,400
He, of course, was very anxious that no one 
should disobey her, or make her angry. If  

551
01:06:02,400 --> 01:06:07,920
she was depressed for a time, he blamed it on 
the illness she had had, and was sympathetic.  

552
01:06:09,040 --> 01:06:15,520
But for most of the time, I believe they 
shared a deep and growing love for each other.

553
01:06:17,360 --> 01:06:25,360
Unfortunately this happiness did not last. 
One evening I was bringing in a basket of  

554
01:06:25,360 --> 01:06:33,200
apples from the garden, when a voice 
behind me said, 'Ellen, is that you?'

555
01:06:34,800 --> 01:06:37,840
It was a deep, rather unusual voice.  

556
01:06:38,800 --> 01:06:46,080
I turned, to see a tall, dark man 
in the shadow near the kitchen door.

557
01:06:46,080 --> 01:06:52,000
'Don't you know me?' he asked. 
'Look, I'm not a stranger!'

558
01:06:53,440 --> 01:06:55,760
'What!' I cried in surprise,  

559
01:06:56,560 --> 01:07:02,720
for it had been four years since he 
disappeared. 'Heathcliff! Is it really you?'

560
01:07:04,160 --> 01:07:08,480
'Yes,' he replied, looking up 
at the windows of the house.  

561
01:07:09,760 --> 01:07:15,920
'Are they at home? Where is she? 
Tell me, Ellen! I must speak to her!'

562
01:07:17,520 --> 01:07:25,200
'I'm not sure if you should see her,' I 
hesitated. 'Will the shock be too much for her?'

563
01:07:26,800 --> 01:07:33,120
'Go and tell her I'm here, Ellen!' he said 
impatiently. 'Don't make me suffer like this!'

564
01:07:34,960 --> 01:07:42,160
I left him at the door, and went upstairs to 
find Mr and Mrs Linton. They were sitting quietly  

565
01:07:42,160 --> 01:07:50,320
together, looking out over the peaceful valley. 
The room, and the view, and the two people,  

566
01:07:51,280 --> 01:07:58,400
seemed so calm that I did not want to disturb 
them. But I had to deliver my message.

567
01:08:00,320 --> 01:08:03,680
'A man wants to see you, madam,' I muttered.

568
01:08:05,280 --> 01:08:08,960
'I'll go downstairs and see 
him then,' replied Catherine.  

569
01:08:09,760 --> 01:08:14,240
'Bring the tea up, Ellen, while 
I'm away.' She left the room.

570
01:08:15,920 --> 01:08:18,480
'Who is it, Ellen?' asked Mr Edgar.

571
01:08:19,680 --> 01:08:25,360
'It's that Heathcliff, sir. You remember, 
he used to live at Wuthering Heights.'

572
01:08:26,560 --> 01:08:31,040
'What! The gipsy, who worked 
on the farm?' he cried.

573
01:08:32,080 --> 01:08:36,720
'Mrs Linton would be angry if she heard 
you talking about him like that, sir.  

574
01:08:37,680 --> 01:08:42,000
She was very upset when he ran away. 
She's very fond of him, you know.'

575
01:08:43,600 --> 01:08:48,160
'Mr Edgar put his head out of the 
window and called to his wife,  

576
01:08:49,600 --> 01:08:54,160
Don't stand there in the cold, love! Bring 
the person in, if it's anyone special.'

577
01:08:55,920 --> 01:08:59,440
Catherine rushed upstairs and into the room,  

578
01:08:59,440 --> 01:09:04,000
wild and breathless. She threw 
her arms round her husband's neck.

579
01:09:05,040 --> 01:09:09,280
'Oh Edgar darling! Heathcliffs come back!'

580
01:09:10,720 --> 01:09:15,680
'Well, well,' said Mr Edgar crossly, 
'there's no need to get excited.'

581
01:09:16,880 --> 01:09:24,000
'I know you didn't like him,' she said, 'but 
please, I beg you to be friends with him now.  

582
01:09:25,280 --> 01:09:26,720
Shall I ask him to come up?'

583
01:09:28,480 --> 01:09:31,280
'You're suggesting inviting him up here,  

584
01:09:31,840 --> 01:09:36,880
into our sitting room? Don't you think 
the kitchen is more suitable for him?'

585
01:09:38,400 --> 01:09:44,560
Catherine looked at her husband, 
half angry and half laughing. 'No,'  

586
01:09:45,600 --> 01:09:54,320
she said, 'I can't sit in the kitchen. Ellen, 
bring two tables, one for your master and Miss  

587
01:09:54,320 --> 01:10:01,040
Isabella, the other for Heathcliff and myself. 
We'll sit apart from them, as we're of a lower  

588
01:10:01,040 --> 01:10:08,080
class! Will that please you, Edgar darling? 
Decide quickly! I must have him near me!'

589
01:10:09,440 --> 01:10:13,040
'Ellen, you go and bring him up,' said Mr Edgar.  

590
01:10:13,680 --> 01:10:19,440
'And Catherine, try not to behave 
foolishly. Remember, he's only a servant!'

591
01:10:21,520 --> 01:10:27,120
When Heathcliff entered the sitting-room, I 
was surprised to see how much he had changed.  

592
01:10:27,920 --> 01:10:35,040
He wore a confident, intelligent expression on 
his face, and his manner was no longer rough.  

593
01:10:36,480 --> 01:10:43,840
Although I recognized the same black fire in 
his eyes, the farm boy had become a gentleman.

594
01:10:44,720 --> 01:10:51,520
Mr Edgar was as surprised as I was, but 
welcomed Heathcliff as politely as he could.  

595
01:10:52,720 --> 01:10:58,080
However, he grew more and more annoyed 
as he watched his wife's delighted face.  

596
01:10:58,880 --> 01:11:01,680
She could not take her eyes off Heathcliff.

597
01:11:03,520 --> 01:11:09,920
'Tomorrow I won't be able to believe that 
I've seen and touched you, Heathcliff!'  

598
01:11:09,920 --> 01:11:12,480
she cried, catching hold of his hands.  

599
01:11:13,600 --> 01:11:20,800
But how cruel of you to run away and keep 
silent for four years, and never think of me!'

600
01:11:22,560 --> 01:11:32,000
'I've thought of you more than you've thought of 
me,' he replied quietly. 'I heard you had married,  

601
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:39,840
Catherine, and I came, just to see you once, and 
then take my revenge on your brother Hindley.  

602
01:11:40,720 --> 01:11:47,600
Your welcome may change my plans. You 
know, I've had a bitter, hard life  

603
01:11:47,600 --> 01:11:53,840
since I last heard your voice, and if 
I've survived, it's all because of you!'

604
01:11:55,360 --> 01:12:02,480
'Catherine,' said Mr Edgar, trying to remain 
polite, 'please pour out the tea, or it will  

605
01:12:02,480 --> 01:12:10,000
be cold. Mr Heathcliff will have a long walk to 
wherever he's staying tonight, and I'm thirsty.'

606
01:12:11,440 --> 01:12:17,520
But Catherine was too excited, and 
Mr Edgar too angry, to drink any tea.  

607
01:12:18,960 --> 01:12:26,800
After a while their guest left. We discovered that 
he had been invited to stay at Wuthering Heights,  

608
01:12:26,800 --> 01:12:33,840
by Hindley. I could not understand why 
Hindley, who hated him, would want his company,  

609
01:12:34,720 --> 01:12:40,560
and I felt sure it would have been better for 
all of us if Heathcliff had never come back.

610
01:12:42,560 --> 01:12:45,840
Catherine could not keep her happiness to herself.  

611
01:12:46,960 --> 01:12:50,800
In the middle of the night she 
woke me to talk about Heathcliff.

612
01:12:52,400 --> 01:12:55,680
'I just can't sleep, Ellen!' she said.  

613
01:12:56,320 --> 01:13:01,040
And Edgar won't listen when I tell 
him how happy I am! He's so selfish!'

614
01:13:02,400 --> 01:13:08,560
'He never liked Heathcliff,' I replied, 'and 
he'll be angry if you go on talking about him.  

615
01:13:09,760 --> 01:13:16,240
You think he's weak, but he could be as determined 
as you, about something he thinks is important.'

616
01:13:17,600 --> 01:13:25,280
'No!' she laughed. 'I have such confidence in 
Edgar's love that I think I could kill him,  

617
01:13:25,280 --> 01:13:31,840
and he wouldn't blame me for it. He will have 
to learn to accept Heathcliff as my friend.'

618
01:13:32,720 --> 01:13:36,160
'Do you know why Heathcliff is 
staying at Wuthering Heights?'

619
01:13:37,200 --> 01:13:41,440
'Oh, yes. He explained that 
he went there to look for me.  

620
01:13:42,480 --> 01:13:47,920
Hindley asked him to play cards, and when 
he discovered Heathcliff had a lot of money,  

621
01:13:48,480 --> 01:13:55,520
invited him to stay there. You know how greedy 
my brother is. He'll make Heathcliff pay rent,  

622
01:13:56,160 --> 01:14:02,400
and hope to win money from him at cards. 
Heathcliff wants to stay there to be near me.  

623
01:14:03,280 --> 01:14:08,880
I'm so happy, Ellen! And I want 
everyone around me to be happy too!'

624
01:14:10,960 --> 01:14:18,640
Catherine behaved so sweetly to her husband in 
the next few days that Thrushcross Grange seemed  

625
01:14:18,640 --> 01:14:25,920
full of sunshine, and in spite of his doubts, Mr 
Edgar allowed Heathcliff to visit her regularly.  

626
01:14:27,040 --> 01:14:32,880
However, Heathcliffs visits produced a 
result which none of us had expected.  

627
01:14:34,240 --> 01:14:42,320
Isabella, Mr Edgar's sister, a pretty girl of 
eighteen, suddenly declared that she was in love  

628
01:14:42,320 --> 01:14:51,440
with Heathcliff. Mr Edgar, who loved her dearly, 
was shocked. He knew that if he and Catherine had  

629
01:14:51,440 --> 01:14:59,840
no sons, Isabella would inherit the considerable 
Linton fortune. He did not like the idea  

630
01:14:59,840 --> 01:15:06,800
of the fortune passing to Heathcliff, as 
Isabella's husband. But more importantly,  

631
01:15:06,800 --> 01:15:13,600
he suspected that Heathcliff was hiding his true 
wickedness under his gentlemanly appearance.

632
01:15:15,760 --> 01:15:22,000
Catherine tried hard to persuade Isabella 
that Heathcliff was not worth loving,  

633
01:15:22,960 --> 01:15:27,920
but poor Isabella was jealous of 
Catherine's relationship with Heathcliff  

634
01:15:27,920 --> 01:15:34,800
and would not listen. Finally, Catherine 
told Heathcliff himself that Isabella  

635
01:15:34,800 --> 01:15:38,880
was in love with him. She thought 
she knew what his answer would be.

636
01:15:40,800 --> 01:15:48,160
'How could I ever love that stupid girl?' he 
asked. 'She has a miserable pale face, and weak  

637
01:15:48,160 --> 01:15:56,320
blue eyes, just like your husband! But... she will 
inherit the family wealth from him, won't she?'

638
01:15:57,520 --> 01:16:02,800
'That's true,' replied Catherine. 'But 
don't think about that, Heathcliff.  

639
01:16:03,680 --> 01:16:08,560
I hope Edgar and I will have several 
sons, and then they will inherit it.'

640
01:16:10,480 --> 01:16:17,920
Catherine did not speak of this matter again, 
but I am sure Heathcliff often thought about it.  

641
01:16:18,880 --> 01:16:25,520
I watched him carefully in the next few days. 
I hoped he would do nothing to hurt Mr Edgar,  

642
01:16:25,520 --> 01:16:32,080
who was a kind master to me. I was worried, too, 
about what was happening at Wuthering Heights.  

643
01:16:33,440 --> 01:16:37,680
Hindley and his son Hareton 
seemed like lost sheep to me,  

644
01:16:38,480 --> 01:16:47,840
and I knew there was a wicked wolf just 
waiting for the chance to attack them.
 
 

645
01:16:48,560 --> 01:16:49,360
